root


âœ… Full system compromise.

ğŸ•µï¸ 4. Credential Sniffing (No Login Required)

An attacker on the same network can steal Telnet credentials without interacting with the victim, using passive network sniffing.

Start capture on the attacker machine (Kali):

sudo tcpdump -i eth0 -A port 23


Then perform a Telnet login from another terminal/machine.

Captured output will reveal:

login: msfadmin
password: msfadmin


âœ… This proves that Telnet exposes credentials in clear text.

Why this matters:

No exploits required

No authentication required

Stealthy attack

Enables further system compromise

ğŸ’¥ Impact
Category	Risk
Confidentiality	Credentials exposed
Integrity	Attacker can modify system files
Availability	Full root access enables disruption
Lateral Movement	Credentials may work across other services
Persistence	Backdoors can be created

Final Result: The attacker gains complete control of the system.

ğŸ”§ 5. Mitigation

âœ… Disable Telnet entirely
âœ… Replace with SSH
âœ… Remove default credentials
âœ… Enforce strong passwords & MFA
âœ… Restrict remote access via firewall
âœ… Implement network segmentation
âœ… Monitor logs & detect suspicious logins

In modern environments, Telnet should never be exposed or used.

ğŸ“š Key Takeaways

Misconfigurations are often more dangerous than exploits

Plaintext protocols are a critical security risk

Attackers can compromise a system without touching passwords directly

Privilege escalation turns "access" into "ownership"

